# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boolean-circuit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] In computational complexity theory and circuit complexity, a **Boolean circuit** is a mathematical model for combinational digital logic circuits.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] A formal language can be decided by a family of Boolean circuits, one circuit for each possible input length.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Boolean circuits are defined in terms of the logic gates they contain.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] For example, a circuit might contain binary AND and OR gates and unary NOT gates, or be entirely described by binary NAND gates.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Each gate corresponds to some Boolean function that takes a fixed number of bits as input and outputs a single bit.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Boolean circuits provide a model for many digital components used in computer engineering, including multiplexers, adders, and arithmetic logic units, but they exclude sequential logic.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] They are an abstraction that omits many aspects relevant to designing real digital logic circuits, such as metastability, fanout, glitches, power consumption, and propagation delay variability.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] In giving a formal definition of Boolean circuits, Vollmer starts by defining a basis as set *B* of Boolean functions, corresponding to the gates allowable in the circuit model.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] A Boolean circuit over a basis *B*, with *n* inputs and *m* outputs, is then defined as a finite directed acyclic graph.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Each vertex corresponds to either a basis function or one of the inputs, and there is a set of exactly *m* nodes which are labeled as the outputs.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] The edges must also have some ordering, to distinguish between different arguments to the same Boolean function.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] As a special case, a propositional formula or Boolean expression is a Boolean circuit with a single output node in which every other node has fan-out of 1.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Thus, a Boolean circuit can be regarded as a generalization that allows shared subformulas and multiple outputs.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] A common basis for Boolean circuits is the set {AND, OR, NOT}, which is functionally complete, i.e. from which all other Boolean functions can be constructed.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] A particular circuit acts only on inputs of fixed size.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] However, formal languages (the string-based representations of decision problems) contain strings of different lengths, so languages cannot be fully captured by a single circuit (in contrast to the Turing machine model, in which a language is fully described by a single Turing machine).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] A language is instead represented by a *circuit family*.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] A circuit family is an infinite list of circuits $(C_{0},C_{1},C_{2},...)$ , where $C_{n}$ has n input variables.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] A circuit family is said to decide a language L if, for every string w , w is in the language L if and only if $C_{n}(w)=1$ , where n is the length of w .
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] In other words, a language is the set of strings which, when applied to the circuits corresponding to their lengths, evaluate to 1.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Several important complexity measures can be defined on Boolean circuits, including circuit depth, circuit size, and the number of alternations between AND gates and OR gates.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] For example, the size complexity of a Boolean circuit is the number of gates in the circuit.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] There is a natural connection between circuit size complexity and time complexity.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Intuitively, a language with small time complexity (that is, requires relatively few sequential operations on a Turing machine), also has a small circuit complexity (that is, requires relatively few Boolean operations).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Formally, it can be shown that if a language is in ${\mathsf {TIME}}(t(n))$ , where t is a function $t:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ , then it has circuit size complexity $O(t^{2}(n))$ .
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Several important complexity classes are defined in terms of Boolean circuits.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] The most general of these is P/poly, the set of languages that are decidable by polynomial-size circuit families.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] It follows directly from the fact that languages in ${\mathsf {TIME}}(t(n))$ have circuit complexity $O(t^{2}(n))$ that P $\subseteq$ P/poly.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] In other words, any problem that can be computed in polynomial time by a deterministic Turing machine can also be computed by a polynomial-size circuit family.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] It is further the case that the inclusion is proper (i.e.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] P $\subsetneq$ P/poly) because there are undecidable problems that are in P/poly.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] P/poly turns out to have a number of properties that make it highly useful in the study of the relationships between complexity classes.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] In particular, it is helpful in investigating problems related to P versus NP.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] For example, if there is any language in NP that is not in P/poly then P $\neq$ NP.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] P/poly also helps to investigate properties of the polynomial hierarchy.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] For example, if NP ⊆ P/poly, then PH collapses to $\Sigma _{2}^{\mathsf {P}}$ .
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] A full description of the relations between P/poly and other complexity classes is available at "Importance of P/poly".
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] P/poly also has the interesting feature that it can be equivalently defined as the class of languages recognized by a polynomial-time Turing machine with a polynomial-bounded advice function.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Two subclasses of P/poly that have interesting properties in their own right are NC and AC.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] These classes are defined not only in terms of their circuit size but also in terms of their *depth*.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] The depth of a circuit is the length of the longest directed path from an input node to the output node.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] The class NC is the set of languages that can be solved by circuit families that are restricted not only to having polynomial-size but also to having polylogarithmic depth.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] The class AC is defined similarly to NC, however gates are allowed to have unbounded fan-in (that is, the AND and OR gates can be applied to more than two bits).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] NC is an important class because it turns out that it represents the class of languages that have efficient parallel algorithms.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] The circuit value problem — the problem of computing the output of a given Boolean circuit on a given input string — is a P-complete decision problem.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Therefore, this problem is considered to be "inherently sequential" in the sense that there is likely no efficient, highly parallel algorithm that solves the problem.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Logic circuits are physical representation of simple logic operations, AND, OR and NOT (and their combinations, such as non-sequential flip-flops or circuit networks), that form a mathematical structure known as Boolean algebra.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] They are complete in sense that they can perform any deterministic algorithm.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] However, it just happens that this is not all there is.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] In the physical world we also encounter randomness, notable in small systems governed by quantization effects, which is described by theory of quantum mechanics.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Logic circuits cannot produce any randomness, and in that sense they form an incomplete logic set.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] Remedy to that is found in adding an ad-hoc random bit generator to logic networks, or computers, such as in probabilistic Turing machine.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] A recent work has introduced a theoretical concept of an inherently random logic circuit named *random flip-flop*, which completes the set.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] It conveniently packs randomness and is inter-operable with deterministic Boolean logic circuits.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-circuit] However, an algebraic structure equivalent of Boolean algebra and associated methods of circuit construction and reduction for the extended set is yet unknown.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] In mathematics, a **Boolean function** is a function whose arguments and result assume values from a two-element set (usually {true, false}, {0,1} or {−1,1}).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] Alternative names are **switching function**, used especially in older computer science literature, and **truth function** (or **logical function)**, used in logic.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] Boolean functions are the subject of Boolean algebra and switching theory.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] A Boolean function takes the form $f:\{0,1\}^{k}\to \{0,1\}$ , where $\{0,1\}$ is known as the Boolean domain and k is a non-negative integer called the arity of the function.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] In the case where $k=0$ , the function is a constant element of $\{0,1\}$ .
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] A Boolean function with multiple outputs, $f:\{0,1\}^{k}\to \{0,1\}^{m}$ with $m>1$ is a **vectorial** or *vector-valued* Boolean function (an S-box in symmetric cryptography).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] There are $2^{2^{k}}$ different Boolean functions with k arguments; equal to the number of different truth tables with $2^{k}$ entries.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] Every k -ary Boolean function can be expressed as a propositional formula in k variables $x_{1},...,x_{k}$ , and two propositional formulas are logically equivalent if and only if they express the same Boolean function.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] An example of a more complicated function is the majority function (of an odd number of inputs).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] In order to optimize electronic circuits, Boolean formulas can be minimized using the Quine–McCluskey algorithm or Karnaugh map.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] Circuit complexity attempts to classify Boolean functions with respect to the size or depth of circuits that can compute them.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] A Boolean function may be decomposed using Boole's expansion theorem in positive and negative *Shannon* *cofactors* (Shannon expansion), which are the (*k*−1)-ary functions resulting from fixing one of the arguments (to 0 or 1).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The general *k*-ary functions obtained by imposing a linear constraint on a set of inputs (a linear subspace) are known as *subfunctions*.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The *Boolean derivative* of the function to one of the arguments is a (*k*−1)-ary function that is true when the output of the function is sensitive to the chosen input variable; it is the XOR of the two corresponding cofactors.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] A derivative and a cofactor are used in a Reed–Muller expansion.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The concept can be generalized as a *k*-ary derivative in the direction dx, obtained as the difference (XOR) of the function at x and x + dx.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The *Möbius transform* (or *Boole–Möbius transform*) of a Boolean function is the set of coefficients of its polynomial (algebraic normal form), as a function of the monomial exponent vectors.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] It can be calculated efficiently using a butterfly algorithm ("*Fast Möbius Transform*"), analogous to the fast Fourier transform.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] *Coincident* Boolean functions are equal to their Möbius transform, i.e. their truth table (minterm) values equal their algebraic (monomial) coefficients.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] There are 2^2^(*k*−1) coincident functions of *k* arguments.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The *Walsh transform* of a Boolean function is a k-ary integer-valued function giving the coefficients of a decomposition into linear functions (Walsh functions), analogous to the decomposition of real-valued functions into harmonics by the Fourier transform.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] Its square is the *power spectrum* or *Walsh spectrum*.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The Walsh coefficient of a single bit vector is a measure for the correlation of that bit with the output of the Boolean function.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The maximum (in absolute value) Walsh coefficient is known as the *linearity* of the function.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The highest number of bits (order) for which all Walsh coefficients are 0 (i.e. the subfunctions are balanced) is known as *resiliency*, and the function is said to be correlation immune to that order.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The Walsh coefficients play a key role in linear cryptanalysis.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The *autocorrelation* of a Boolean function is a k-ary integer-valued function giving the correlation between a certain set of changes in the inputs and the function output.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] For a given bit vector it is related to the Hamming weight of the derivative in that direction.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The maximal autocorrelation coefficient (in absolute value) is known as the *absolute indicator*.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] If all autocorrelation coefficients are 0 (i.e. the derivatives are balanced) for a certain number of bits then the function is said to satisfy the *propagation criterion* to that order; if they are all zero then the function is a bent function.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The autocorrelation coefficients play a key role in differential cryptanalysis.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The Walsh coefficients of a Boolean function and its autocorrelation coefficients are related by the equivalent of the Wiener–Khinchin theorem, which states that the autocorrelation and the power spectrum are a Walsh transform pair.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] These concepts can be extended naturally to *vectorial* Boolean functions by considering their output bits (*coordinates*) individually, or more thoroughly, by looking at the set of all linear functions of output bits, known as its *components*.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The set of Walsh transforms of the components is known as a **linear approximation table** (LAT) or *correlation matrix*; it describes the correlation between different linear combinations of input and output bits.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The set of autocorrelation coefficients of the components is the *autocorrelation table*, related by a Walsh transform of the components to the more widely used *difference distribution table* (DDT) which lists the correlations between differences in input and output bits (see also: S-box).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] When all operands are independent (share no variables) a function's polynomial form can be found by repeatedly applying the polynomials of the operators in a Boolean formula.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] When the coefficients are calculated modulo 2 one obtains the algebraic normal form (Zhegalkin polynomial).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] Taken modulo 2, this is the Boolean *Möbius transform*, giving the algebraic normal form coefficients: ${\hat {f}}(m)=\bigoplus _{a\subseteq m}f(a)$ In both cases, the sum is taken over all bit-vectors *a* covered by *m*, i.e. the "one" bits of *a* form a subset of the one bits of *m*.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] When the domain is restricted to the n-dimensional hypercube $[0,1]^{n}$ , the polynomial $f^{*}(x):[0,1]^{n}\rightarrow [0,1]$ gives the probability of a positive outcome when the Boolean function *f* is applied to *n* independent random (Bernoulli) variables, with individual probabilities *x*.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] A special case of this fact is the piling-up lemma for parity functions.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The polynomial form of a Boolean function can also be used as its natural extension to fuzzy logic.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] Often, the Boolean domain is taken as $\{-1,1\}$ , with false ("0") mapping to 1 and true ("1") to −1 (see Analysis of Boolean functions).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] This polynomial form thus corresponds to the *Walsh transform* (in this context also known as *Fourier transform*) of the function (see above).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The polynomial also has the same statistical interpretation as the one in the standard Boolean domain, except that it now deals with the expected values $E(X)=P(X=1)-P(X=-1)\in [-1,1]$ (see piling-up lemma for an example).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] Boolean functions play a basic role in questions of complexity theory as well as the design of processors for digital computers, where they are implemented in electronic circuits using logic gates.
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] The properties of Boolean functions are critical in cryptography, particularly in the design of symmetric key algorithms (see substitution box).
[src:boolean-circuit/boolean-function] In cooperative game theory, monotone Boolean functions are called **simple games** (voting games); this notion is applied to solve problems in social choice theory.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] In theoretical computer science, the **circuit satisfiability problem** (also known as **CIRCUIT-SAT**, **CircuitSAT**, **CSAT**, etc.) is the decision problem of determining whether a given Boolean circuit has an assignment of its inputs that makes the output true.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] In other words, it asks whether the inputs to a given Boolean circuit can be consistently set to **1** or **0** such that the circuit outputs **1**.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] If that is the case, the circuit is called *satisfiable*.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Otherwise, the circuit is called *unsatisfiable.* In the figure to the right, the left circuit can be satisfied by setting both inputs to be **1**, but the right circuit is unsatisfiable.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] CircuitSAT is closely related to the Boolean satisfiability problem (SAT), and likewise, has been proven to be NP-complete.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] It is a prototypical NP-complete problem; the Cook–Levin theorem is sometimes proved on CircuitSAT instead of on the SAT, and then CircuitSAT can be reduced to the other satisfiability problems to prove their NP-completeness.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] The satisfiability of a circuit containing m arbitrary binary gates can be decided in time $O(2^{0.4058m})$ .
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Given a circuit and a satisfying set of inputs, one can compute the output of each gate in constant time.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Hence, the output of the circuit is verifiable in polynomial time.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Thus Circuit SAT belongs to complexity class NP.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] To show NP-hardness, it is possible to construct a reduction from 3SAT to Circuit SAT.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Design a circuit such that it has an input corresponding to every variable and a gate corresponding to every operator.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Connect the gates according to the 3SAT formula.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] For instance, if the 3SAT formula is $(\lnot x_{1}\land x_{2})\lor x_{3},$ the circuit will have 3 inputs, one AND, one OR, and one NOT gate.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Notice that the 3SAT formula is equivalent to the circuit designed above, hence their output is same for same input.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Hence, If the 3SAT formula has a satisfying assignment, then the corresponding circuit will output 1, and vice versa.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] So, this is a valid reduction, and Circuit SAT is NP-hard.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] This completes the proof that circuit SAT is NP-Complete.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Assume that we are given a planar Boolean circuit (i.e. a Boolean circuit whose underlying graph is planar) containing only NAND gates with exactly two inputs.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Planar Circuit SAT is the decision problem of determining whether this circuit has an assignment of its inputs that makes the output true.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Moreover, if the restrictions are changed so that any gate in the circuit is a NOR gate, the resulting problem remains NP-complete.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Circuit UNSAT is the decision problem of determining whether a given Boolean circuit outputs false for all possible assignments of its inputs.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] This is the complement of the Circuit SAT problem, and is therefore co-NP-complete.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Reduction from CircuitSAT or its variants can be used to show NP-hardness of certain problems, and provides us with an alternative to dual-rail and binary logic reductions.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] This problem asks whether it is possible to locate all the bombs given a Minesweeper board.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] It has been proven to be co-NP-complete via a reduction from circuit UNSAT problem.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] The gadgets constructed for this reduction are: wire, split, AND and NOT gates and terminator.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] There are three crucial observations regarding these gadgets.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] First, the split gadget can also be used as the NOT gadget and the turn gadget.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Second, constructing AND and NOT gadgets is sufficient, because together they can simulate the universal NAND gate.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] Finally, since three NANDs can be composed intersection-free to implement an XOR, and since XOR is enough to build a crossover, this gives us the needed crossover gadget.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] The Tseytin transformation is a straightforward reduction from Circuit-SAT to SAT.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] These clauses completely describe the relationship between the three variables.
[src:boolean-circuit/circuit-satisfiability-problem] The converse—that SAT is reducible to circuit-SAT—follows trivially by rewriting the Boolean formula as a circuit and solving it.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] In automata theory, **combinational logic** (also referred to as **time-independent logic**) is a type of digital logic that is implemented by Boolean circuits, where the output is a pure function of the present input only.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] This is in contrast to sequential logic, in which the output depends not only on the present input but also on the history of the input.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] In other words, sequential logic has *memory* while combinational logic does not.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] Combinational logic is used in computer circuits to perform Boolean algebra on input signals and on stored data.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] Practical computer circuits normally contain a mixture of combinational and sequential logic.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] For example, the part of an arithmetic logic unit, or ALU, that does mathematical calculations is constructed using combinational logic.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] Other circuits used in computers, such as half adders, full adders, half subtractors, full subtractors, multiplexers, demultiplexers, encoders and decoders are also made by using combinational logic.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] Practical design of combinational logic systems may require consideration of the finite time required for practical logical elements to react to changes in their inputs.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] Where an output is the result of the combination of several different paths with differing numbers of switching elements, the output may momentarily change state before settling at the final state, as the changes propagate along different paths.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] Combinational logic is used to build circuits that produce specified outputs from certain inputs.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] The construction of combinational logic is generally done using one of two methods: a sum of products, or a product of sums.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] Consider the following truth table, which represents a 3-input combinatorial logic element taking inputs A, B, and C, and with an output which is true only when both input A is true, and inputs B and C are either both true or both false.
[src:boolean-circuit/combinational-logic] With the use of minimization (sometimes called logic optimization), a simplified logical function or circuit may be arrived upon, and the logic combinational circuit becomes smaller, and easier to analyse, use, or build.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] A **logic gate** is a device that performs a Boolean function, a logical operation performed on one or more binary inputs that produces a single binary output.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Depending on the context, the term may refer to an **ideal logic gate**, one that has, for instance, zero rise time and unlimited fan-out, or it may refer to a non-ideal physical device (see ideal and real op-amps for comparison).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The primary way of building logic gates uses diodes or transistors acting as electronic switches.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Today, most logic gates are made from MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] They can also be constructed using vacuum tubes, electromagnetic relays with relay logic, fluidic logic, pneumatic logic, optics, molecules, acoustics, or even mechanical or thermal elements.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Logic gates can be cascaded in the same way that Boolean functions can be composed, allowing the construction of a physical model of all of Boolean logic, and therefore, all of the algorithms and mathematics that can be described with Boolean logic.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] **Logic circuits** include such devices as multiplexers, registers, arithmetic logic units (ALUs), and computer memory, all the way up through complete microprocessors, which may contain more than 100 million logic gates.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Compound logic gates AND-OR-invert (AOI) and OR-AND-invert (OAI) are often employed in circuit design because their construction using MOSFETs is simpler and more efficient than the sum of the individual gates.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] There are seven basic logic gates: NOT, OR, NOR (Negation of the OR statement), AND, NAND (Negation of the AND statement), XOR (Exclusive OR), XNOR (Negation of the Exclusive OR statement).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The binary number system was refined by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz (published in 1705), influenced by the ancient *I Ching*'s binary system.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Leibniz established that using the binary system combined the principles of arithmetic and logic.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The analytical engine devised by Charles Babbage in 1837 used mechanical logic gates based on gears.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] In an 1886 letter, Charles Sanders Peirce described how logical operations could be carried out by electrical switching circuits.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Early Electromechanical computers were constructed from switches and relay logic rather than the later innovations of vacuum tubes (thermionic valves) or transistors (from which later electronic computers were constructed).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Ludwig Wittgenstein introduced a version of the 16-row truth table as proposition 5.101 of *Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus* (1921).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Walther Bothe, inventor of the coincidence circuit, got part of the 1954 Nobel Prize in physics, for the first modern electronic AND gate in 1924.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Konrad Zuse designed and built electromechanical logic gates for his computer Z1 (from 1935 to 1938).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] From 1934 to 1936, NEC engineer Akira Nakashima, Claude Shannon and Victor Shestakov introduced switching circuit theory in a series of papers showing that two-valued Boolean algebra, which they discovered independently, can describe the operation of switching circuits.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Using this property of electrical switches to implement logic is the fundamental concept that underlies all electronic digital computers.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Switching circuit theory became the foundation of digital circuit design, as it became widely known in the electrical engineering community during and after World War II, with theoretical rigor superseding the *ad hoc* methods that had prevailed previously.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] In 1948, Bardeen and Brattain patented an insulated-gate transistor (IGFET) with an inversion layer.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Their concept forms the basis of CMOS technology today.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] In 1957, Frosch and Derick were able to manufacture PMOS and NMOS planar gates.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Later a team at Bell Labs demonstrated a working MOS with PMOS and NMOS gates.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Both types were later combined and adapted into complementary MOS (CMOS) logic by Chih-Tang Sah and Frank Wanlass at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1963.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] There are two sets of symbols for elementary logic gates in common use, both defined in ANSI/IEEE Std 91-1984 and its supplement ANSI/IEEE Std 91a-1991.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The "distinctive shape" set, based on traditional schematics, is used for simple drawings and derives from United States Military Standard MIL-STD-806 of the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] It is sometimes unofficially described as "military", reflecting its origin.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The "rectangular shape" set, based on ANSI Y32.14 and other early industry standards as later refined by IEEE and IEC, has rectangular outlines for all types of gate and allows representation of a much wider range of devices than is possible with the traditional symbols.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The mutual goal of IEEE Std 91-1984 and IEC 617-12 was to provide a uniform method of describing the complex logic functions of digital circuits with schematic symbols.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] These functions were more complex than simple AND and OR gates.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] They could be medium-scale circuits such as a 4-bit counter to a large-scale circuit such as a microprocessor.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] IEC 617-12 and its renumbered successor IEC 60617-12 do not explicitly show the "distinctive shape" symbols, but do not prohibit them.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Usage of these other symbols in combination to form complex symbols (for example, use as embedded symbols) is discouraged." This compromise was reached between the respective IEEE and IEC working groups to permit the IEEE and IEC standards to be in mutual compliance with one another.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] In the 1980s, schematics were the predominant method to design both circuit boards and custom ICs known as gate arrays.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Today custom ICs and the field-programmable gate array are typically designed with Hardware Description Languages (HDL) such as Verilog or VHDL.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] By use of De Morgan's laws, an *AND* function is identical to an *OR* function with negated inputs and outputs.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Likewise, an *OR* function is identical to an *AND* function with negated inputs and outputs.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] A NAND gate is equivalent to an OR gate with negated inputs, and a NOR gate is equivalent to an AND gate with negated inputs.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] This leads to an alternative set of symbols for basic gates that use the opposite core symbol (*AND* or *OR*) but with the inputs and outputs negated.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Use of these alternative symbols can make logic circuit diagrams much clearer and help to show accidental connection of an active high output to an active low input or vice versa.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Any connection that has logic negations at both ends can be replaced by a negationless connection and a suitable change of gate or vice versa.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Any connection that has a negation at one end and no negation at the other can be made easier to interpret by instead using the De Morgan equivalent symbol at either of the two ends.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] When negation or polarity indicators on both ends of a connection match, there is no logic negation in that path (effectively, bubbles "cancel"), making it easier to follow logic states from one symbol to the next.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] This is commonly seen in real logic diagrams – thus the reader must not get into the habit of associating the shapes exclusively as OR or AND shapes, but also take into account the bubbles at both inputs and outputs in order to determine the "true" logic function indicated.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] A De Morgan symbol can show more clearly a gate's primary logical purpose and the polarity of its nodes that are considered in the "signaled" (active, on) state.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Consider the simplified case where a two-input NAND gate is used to drive a motor when either of its inputs are brought low by a switch.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The "signaled" state (motor on) occurs when either one OR the other switch is on.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Unlike a regular NAND symbol, which suggests AND logic, the De Morgan version, a two negative-input OR gate, correctly shows that OR is of interest.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The regular NAND symbol has a bubble at the output and none at the inputs (the opposite of the states that will turn the motor on), but the De Morgan symbol shows both inputs and output in the polarity that will drive the motor.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] De Morgan's theorem is most commonly used to implement logic gates as combinations of only NAND gates, or as combinations of only NOR gates, for economic reasons.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Charles Sanders Peirce (during 1880–1881) showed that NOR gates alone (or alternatively NAND gates alone) can be used to reproduce the functions of all the other logic gates, but his work on it was unpublished until 1933.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The first published proof was by Henry M.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Sheffer in 1913, so the NAND logical operation is sometimes called *Sheffer stroke*; the logical NOR is sometimes called *Peirce's arrow*.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Consequently, these gates are sometimes called *universal logic gates*.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Logic gates can also be used to hold a state, allowing data storage.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] A storage element can be constructed by connecting several gates in a "latch" circuit.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Latching circuitry is used in static random-access memory.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] More complicated designs that use clock signals and that change only on a rising or falling edge of the clock are called edge-triggered "flip-flops".
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Formally, a flip-flop is called a bistable circuit, because it has two stable states which it can maintain indefinitely.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The combination of multiple flip-flops in parallel, used to store a multiple-bit value, is known as a register.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] When using any of these gate setups the overall system has memory; it is then called a sequential logic system since its output can be influenced by its previous state(s), i.e. by the *sequence* of input states.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] In contrast, the output from combinational logic is purely a combination of its present inputs, unaffected by the previous input and output states.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] These logic circuits are used in computer memory.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] They vary in performance, based on factors of speed, complexity, and reliability of storage, and many different types of designs are used based on the application.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] A functionally complete logic system may be composed of relays, valves (vacuum tubes), or transistors.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Electronic logic gates differ significantly from their relay-and-switch equivalents.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] They are much faster, consume much less power, and are much smaller (all by a factor of a million or more in most cases).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Also, there is a fundamental structural difference.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The switch circuit creates a continuous metallic path for current to flow (in either direction) between its input and its output.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The semiconductor logic gate, on the other hand, acts as a high-gain voltage amplifier, which sinks a tiny current at its input and produces a low-impedance voltage at its output.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] It is not possible for current to flow between the output and the input of a semiconductor logic gate.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] For small-scale logic, designers now use prefabricated logic gates from families of devices such as the TTL 7400 series by Texas Instruments, the CMOS 4000 series by RCA, and their more recent descendants.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Increasingly, these fixed-function logic gates are being replaced by programmable logic devices, which allow designers to pack many mixed logic gates into a single integrated circuit.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] An important advantage of standardized integrated circuit logic families, such as the 7400 and 4000 families, is that they can be cascaded.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] This means that the output of one gate can be wired to the inputs of one or several other gates, and so on.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Systems with varying degrees of complexity can be built without great concern of the designer for the internal workings of the gates, provided the limitations of each integrated circuit are considered.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The output of one gate can only drive a finite number of inputs to other gates, a number called the "fan-out limit".
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Also, there is always a delay, called the "propagation delay", from a change in input of a gate to the corresponding change in its output.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] When gates are cascaded, the total propagation delay is approximately the sum of the individual delays, an effect which can become a problem in high-speed synchronous circuits.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Additional delay can be caused when many inputs are connected to an output, due to the distributed capacitance of all the inputs and wiring and the finite amount of current that each output can provide.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] There are several logic families with different characteristics (power consumption, speed, cost, size) such as: RDL (resistor–diode logic), RTL (resistor–transistor logic), DTL (diode–transistor logic), TTL (transistor–transistor logic) and CMOS.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] There are also sub-variants, e.g. standard CMOS logic vs. advanced types using still CMOS technology, but with some optimizations for avoiding loss of speed due to slower PMOS transistors.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The simplest family of logic gates uses bipolar transistors, and is called resistor–transistor logic (RTL).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Unlike simple diode logic gates (which do not have a gain element), RTL gates can be cascaded indefinitely to produce more complex logic functions.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] RTL gates were used in early integrated circuits.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] For higher speed and better density, the resistors used in RTL were replaced by diodes resulting in diode–transistor logic (DTL).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Transistor–transistor logic (TTL) then supplanted DTL.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] As integrated circuits became more complex, bipolar transistors were replaced with smaller field-effect transistors (MOSFETs); see PMOS and NMOS.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] To reduce power consumption still further, most contemporary chip implementations of digital systems now use CMOS logic.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] CMOS uses complementary (both n-channel and p-channel) MOSFET devices to achieve a high speed with low power dissipation.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] A three-state logic gate is a type of logic gate that can have three different outputs: high (H), low (L) and high-impedance (Z).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] The high-impedance state plays no role in the logic, which is strictly binary.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] These devices are used on buses of the CPU to allow multiple chips to send data.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] A group of three-state outputs driving a line with a suitable control circuit is basically equivalent to a multiplexer, which may be physically distributed over separate devices or plug-in cards.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] In electronics, a high output would mean the output is sourcing current from the positive power terminal (positive voltage).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] A low output would mean the output is sinking current to the negative power terminal (zero voltage).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] High impedance would mean that the output is effectively disconnected from the circuit.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Non-electronic implementations are varied, though few of them are used in practical applications.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Many early electromechanical digital computers, such as the Harvard Mark I, were built from relay logic gates, using electro-mechanical relays.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Logic gates can be made using pneumatic devices, such as the Sorteberg relay or mechanical logic gates, including on a molecular scale.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Various types of fundamental logic gates have been constructed using molecules (molecular logic gates), which are based on chemical inputs and spectroscopic outputs.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Logic gates have been made out of DNA (see DNA nanotechnology) and used to create a computer called MAYA (see MAYA-II).
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Logic gates can be made from quantum mechanical effects, see quantum logic gate.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Photonic logic gates use nonlinear optical effects.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] In principle any method that leads to a gate that is functionally complete (for example, either a NOR or a NAND gate) can be used to make any kind of digital logic circuit.
[src:boolean-circuit/logic-gate] Note that the use of 3-state logic for bus systems is not needed, and can be replaced by digital multiplexers, which can be built using only simple logic gates (such as NAND gates, NOR gates, or AND and OR gates).
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] In theoretical computer science, **circuit complexity** is a branch of computational complexity theory in which Boolean functions are classified according to the size or depth of the Boolean circuits that compute them.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] A related notion is the circuit complexity of a recursive language that is decided by a **uniform** family of circuits $C_{1},C_{2},\ldots$ (see below).
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Proving lower bounds on size of Boolean circuits computing explicit Boolean functions is a popular approach to separating complexity classes.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] For example, a prominent circuit class P/poly consists of Boolean functions computable by circuits of polynomial size.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Proving that ${\mathsf {NP}}\not \subseteq {\mathsf {P/poly}}$ would separate P and NP (see below).
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Complexity classes defined in terms of Boolean circuits include AC0, AC, TC0, NC1, NC, and P/poly.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] A Boolean circuit with n input bits is a directed acyclic graph in which every node (usually called *gates* in this context) is either an input node of in-degree 0 labelled by one of the n input bits, an AND gate, an OR gate, or a NOT gate.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] One of these gates is designated as the output gate.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Such a circuit naturally computes a function of its n inputs.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] The **size** of a circuit is the number of gates it contains and its **depth** is the maximal length of a path from an input gate to the output gate.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] There are two major notions of circuit complexity.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] The **circuit-size complexity** of a Boolean function f is the minimal size of any circuit computing f .
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] The **circuit-depth complexity** of a Boolean function f is the minimal depth of any circuit computing f .
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] These notions generalize when one considers the circuit complexity of any formal language that contains strings with different bit lengths, especially infinite languages.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Boolean circuits, however, only allow a fixed number of input bits.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Thus, no single Boolean circuit is capable of deciding such a language.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] To account for this possibility, one considers families of circuits $C_{1},C_{2},\ldots$ where each $C_{n}$ accepts inputs of size n .
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Each circuit family will naturally generate the language by circuit $C_{n}$ outputting 1 when a length n string is a member of the family, and 0 otherwise.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] We say that a family of circuits is **size minimal** if there is no other family that decides on inputs of any size, n , with a circuit of smaller size than $C_{n}$ (respectively for **depth minimal** families).
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Thus, circuit complexity is meaningful even for non-recursive languages.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] The notion of a **uniform family** enables variants of circuit complexity to be related to algorithm-based complexity measures of recursive languages.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] However, the non-uniform variant is helpful to find lower bounds on how complex any circuit family must be in order to decide given languages.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Hence, the **circuit-size complexity** of a formal language A is defined as the function $t:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ , that relates a bit length of an input, n , to the circuit-size complexity of a minimal circuit $C_{n}$ that decides whether inputs of that length are in A .
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] The **circuit-depth complexity** is defined similarly.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] An individual computational problem is thus associated with a particular *family* of Boolean circuits $C_{1},C_{2},\dots$ where each $C_{n}$ is the circuit handling inputs of *n* bits.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] A *uniformity* condition is often imposed on these families, requiring the existence of some possibly resource-bounded Turing machine that, on input *n*, produces a description of the individual circuit $C_{n}$ .
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] When this Turing machine has a running time polynomial in *n*, the circuit family is said to be P-uniform.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] The stricter requirement of DLOGTIME-uniformity is of particular interest in the study of shallow-depth circuit-classes such as AC0 or TC0.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] When no resource bounds are specified, a language is recursive (i.e., decidable by a Turing machine) if and only if the language is decided by a uniform family of Boolean circuits.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Circuit complexity goes back to Shannon in 1949, who proved that almost all Boolean functions on *n* variables require circuits of size Θ(2*n*/*n*).
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Despite this fact, complexity theorists have so far been unable to prove a superlinear lower bound for any explicit function.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Superpolynomial lower bounds have been proved under certain restrictions on the family of circuits used.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] The first function for which superpolynomial circuit lower bounds were shown was the parity function, which computes the sum of its input bits modulo 2.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] The fact that parity is not contained in AC0 was first established independently by Ajtai in 1983 and by Furst, Saxe and Sipser in 1984.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Later improvements by Håstad in 1987 established that any family of constant-depth circuits computing the parity function requires exponential size.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Extending a result of Razborov, Smolensky in 1987 proved that this is true even if the circuit is augmented with gates computing the sum of its input bits modulo some odd prime *p*.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] The *k*-clique problem is to decide whether a given graph on *n* vertices has a clique of size *k*.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] For any particular choice of the constants *n* and *k*, the graph can be encoded in binary using ${n \choose 2}$ bits, which indicate for each possible edge whether it is present.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Then the *k*-clique problem is formalized as a function $f_{k}:\{0,1\}^{n \choose 2}\to \{0,1\}$ such that $f_{k}$ outputs 1 if and only if the graph encoded by the string contains a clique of size *k*.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] This family of functions is monotone and can be computed by a family of circuits, but it has been shown that it cannot be computed by a polynomial-size family of monotone circuits (that is, circuits with AND and OR gates but without negation).
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] The original result of Razborov in 1985 was later improved to an exponential-size lower bound by Alon and Boppana in 1987.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] In 2008, Rossman showed that constant-depth circuits with AND, OR, and NOT gates require size $\Omega (n^{k/4})$ to solve the *k*-clique problem even in the average case.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Moreover, there is a circuit of size $n^{k/4+O(1)}$ that computes $f_{k}$ .
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] In 1999, Raz and McKenzie later showed that the monotone NC hierarchy is infinite.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] The integer division problem lies in uniform TC0.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Circuit lower bounds are generally difficult.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] It is open whether NEXPTIME has nonuniform TC0 circuits.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Proofs of circuit lower bounds are strongly connected to derandomization.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] A proof that ${\mathsf {P}}={\mathsf {BPP}}$ would imply that either ${\mathsf {NEXP}}\not \subseteq {\mathsf {P/poly}}$ or that the permanent of a matrix cannot be computed by nonuniform arithmetic circuits (polynomials) of polynomial size and polynomial degree.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] In 1997, Razborov and Rudich showed that many known circuit lower bounds for explicit Boolean functions imply the existence of so called natural properties useful against the respective circuit class.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] On the other hand, natural properties useful against P/poly would break strong pseudorandom generators.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] This is often interpreted as a "natural proofs" barrier for proving strong circuit lower bounds.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] In 2016, Carmosino, Impagliazzo, Kabanets and Kolokolova proved that natural properties can be also used to construct efficient learning algorithms.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Many circuit complexity classes are defined in terms of class hierarchies.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] For each non-negative integer *i*, there is a class NCi, consisting of polynomial-size circuits of depth $O(\log ^{i}(n))$ , using bounded fan-in AND, OR, and NOT gates.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] The union NC of all of these classes is a subject of study.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] By considering unbounded fan-in gates, the classes ACi and AC (which is equal to NC) can be constructed.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] Many other circuit complexity classes with the same size and depth restrictions can be constructed by allowing different sets of gates.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] If a certain language, A , belongs to the time-complexity class ${\text{TIME}}(t(n))$ for some function $t:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ , then A has circuit complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(t(n)\log t(n))$ .
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] If the Turing Machine that accepts the language is oblivious (meaning that it reads and writes the same memory cells regardless of input), then A has circuit complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(t(n))$ .
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] A monotone Boolean circuit is one that has only AND and OR gates, but no NOT gates.
[src:boolean-circuit/monotone-circuit] A monotone circuit can only compute a monotone Boolean function, which is a function $f:\{0,1\}^{n}\to \{0,1\}$ where for every $x,y\in \{0,1\}^{n}$ , $x\leq y\implies f(x)\leq f(y)$ , where $x\leq y$ means that $x_{i}\leq y_{i}$ for all $i\in \{1,\ldots ,n\}$ .
